OPEN LETTER TO P.J. VIETNAM VETERAN COUNSELOR;<br><br>
Dear P.J.:<br><br>
It was a pleasure to have spoken to you yesterday and I'm looking forward to hearing from you upon your return from the land of no postage stamps.  I'm excited for you and the opportunity you have to visit the areas where we not only engaged the enemy but where we shared so many memories. <br><br>
Many Vietnam veterans have never taken the time to think through much of what transpired at that time.  History's shame denied us the right to share those memories with our love ones and the same military service that brought us together annulled our common bonds. With the publication of the book I hope to help the American public feel what we felt, to see what we saw and Marines to reflect upon those common times and to once again embrace that friendship born under the chaos of war which both tore us apart but also made us one.  <br><br>
Since I begun to contact former Marines that served with us during our tour of duty, old memories have been refreshed and for many it has become a genuine beginning for a time to heal.<br><br>
The following is from the book, (unedited), Fields of Fire, Dreams of Glory:<br><br>
June 26th, 1968, OKINAWA <br>
When I arrived at Okinawa, I ran into Benevedo and Bennet who were also on their way home. I hadn't seen them in thirteen months. They had served their tour of duty with the 3rd Marine Division near the DMZ, but that's another story, another diary that for now, remains written only in their hearts and minds. Perhaps one day they will share with us their fields of fire and their dreams of glory. <br>
We were the fortunate ones, the survivors.  No one else from our old 101 platoon series at MCRD made it back without being killed or seriously wounded. <br>
While I was in Vietnam I realized that I had made a difference.  There are Marines alive today that wouldn't be if I hadn't volunteered for duty, If I hadn't believed in my country and in what we were doing there. Ronald Allen Moore (Bro), gave his life when he volunteered in my place and today his name is etched on that black reflective wall in Washington, D.C. I had a chance to visit that wall a few years back and it had a profound effect on me. The tears I never shed in war, the love I never gave, the moments lost and pains and sorrows shared were all bottled up and released on that day. All Viet Nam veterans should experience such a healing and finally make peace with the past and move on toward the future.... <br><br>
I hope to finish the editing process soon after you return and your contribution would of course be very helpful.  The book is a non-fiction account of a Marine infantry platoon during the time we served. It covers the 13 months I served in Viet Nam, June 1967-July 1968.  <br><br>
I have been able to obtained some Marine Corps after action reports of certain events of that time. Many Marines that SERVED IN 1st, 2ND, 3RD as well as in weapon's platoon have also contributed from their recollection of those events and I have been able to incorporate some of those memories into what I had already described in the book. I look forward to speaking once again with you and to further gain your insight as well. <br><br>
Sincerely <br><br>
&quot;Cookie&quot; Barela<br>
India Company, 3/7 1st Marine Division<br>

